sued to gain equality. She challenges the popular “wave” theory, concluding that feminist activism was continuous, despite changing significantly across decades. Demanding Equality presents a picture of a heterogeneous movement characterized by both alliances and fierce internal debates. This comprehensive rear-view look at feminism in all its political guises encourages a wider public conversation about what Canadian feminism has been, is, and should be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismzCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aFeminismzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFeministszCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aFeministszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aWomenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311141764640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486608840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774866088423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774866088/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-141764-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles